Name: Andorra
Snippet: A tiny land-locked country in the Pyrenees mountains, popular for skiing in the winter, hiking in the summer, and shopping all year long.

Name: United Arab Emirates
Snippet: A major hub of oil shipping and foreign labor that includes the famous skylines of Dubai and Abu Dhabi and quieter, more traditional emirates like Sharjah.

Name: Afghanistan
Snippet: One-time backpacker Shangri-La, but bloody (and ongoing) war, famine, and nightmare politics since the late 1970s have left it with considerably less appeal for travellers.

Name: Antigua and Barbuda
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Antigua, Saint John's and English Harbour.

Name: Anguilla
Snippet: Known for dinner. Recommended places to visit are Heritage Collection Museum, The Valley and Sandy Ground.

Name: Albania
Snippet: A beautiful and diverse country with impressive castles, long coastlines and a unique culture and history.

Name: Armenia
Snippet: An ancient, millennia-old civilization amidst stark mountain landscapes and remote canyons.

Name: Angola
Snippet: Former Portuguese colony which went through a brutal civil war. Now largely safe, it has been surprisingly slow to appear on the tourist radar.

Name: Argentina
Snippet: Once known for being a 'European nation in South America', Argentina offers a dynamic and rich cultural life in its cities, and sparsely-populated grasslands, mountains and glacial parks in the south.

Name: American Samoa
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Pago Pago, Tutuila and Fagatogo.

Name: Austria
Snippet: Forget "the sound of music" (few Austrians have ever actually heard of it), this country has much more to offer than breathtaking alpine panoramas - the cosmopolitan city of Vienna has a unique charm and Vienna coffee houses were both the start of many a story and the place where they were written.

Name: Australia
Snippet: The largest and most populous country in Oceania, often considered a continent by itself.

Name: Aruba
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Aruba Natural Bridge, California Lighthouse and Alto Vista Chapel.

Name: Azerbaijan
Snippet: The richest state of the Caucasus, its capital awash in oil wealth and international business, wonderful old palaces of the Shirvan Shahs in Baku and Sheki, Zoroastrian fire temples, barren landscapes—oil and salt spreading across the surface, and world-class hikes in the lush, heavily forested, mountainous north and south.

Name: Bosnia and Herzegovina
Snippet: A political hotbed, but also an impressive mix of cultures with beautiful historic cities.

Name: Barbados
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Harrison's Cave, Bridgetown and Morgan Lewis Windmill.

Name: Bangladesh
Snippet: Home of beautiful mangroves and the world's longest beach.

Name: Belgium
Snippet: The battlefield for World War I, this picturesque country is known for its culinary specialties and hosts many important institutions of the European Union.

Name: Burkina Faso
Snippet: Landlocked country that is very off the beaten path for visitors.

Name: Bulgaria
Snippet: A melting pot of East and West, with beautiful beaches.

Name: Bahrain
Snippet: This island state, the smallest of the Gulf emirates, is known in the region as the playground for visitors from its more conservative neighbors.

Name: Burundi
Snippet: On the shores of Lake Tanganyika; largely deforested and has precious little to interest the visitor.

Name: Benin
Snippet: A safe and relatively easy country for travellers to visit; birthplace of the Voodoo religion and former home of the Kingdom of Dahomey.

Name: Bermuda
Snippet: Small and wealthy British overseas territory in the Atlantic, known for a type of shorts and the supposedly mysterious triangle.

Name: Brunei
Snippet: A tiny, oil-rich sultanate in Borneo, little visited but full of tranquil mosques and cultural sites not yet commodified by mass tourism.

Name: Bolivia
Snippet: This landlocked country is arguably the only one in Latin America with an ethnic majority of indigenous people, and a culture that is much affected by the high altitude of the Andes.

Name: Brazil
Snippet: South America's only Portuguese-speaking country is also its biggest, offering the Amazon rainforest along with vibrant cities such as Rio de Janeiro.

Name: The Bahamas
Snippet: Archipelago of islands and cays surrounded by coral reefs off the coasts of Florida.

Name: Bhutan
Snippet: A Buddhist-majority country influenced by the Tibetan culture and way of life.

Name: Botswana
Snippet: Famous for the rich wildlife of the Okavango Delta.

Name: Belarus
Snippet: Known for museums. Recommended places to visit are Minsk, Brest and Grodno.

Name: Belize
Snippet: The only Central American country without a Pacific coast line, and the only one where English is the official language.

Name: Canada
Snippet: The Great White North certainly has vast expanses of unspoiled wilderness, but it also features some of the world's most modern, cosmopolitan cities.

Name: Democratic Republic of the Congo
Snippet: Huge, blessed with incredible natural wealth and beauty, culturally diverse, and is extremely unstable and dangerous.

Name: Central African Republic
Snippet: Dense jungle in the south and semi arid in the Sahelian north, this very unstable country is very much off the radar for visitors.

Name: Republic of the Congo
Snippet: Huge tracts of forest with a small population mean great potential for eco-tourism, but the country has not fully recovered from a terrible war in the 1990s.

Name: Switzerland
Snippet: With four official languages and strong regional identities in over two dozen cantons, Switzerland is one of the most diverse countries in Europe.

Name: Ivory Coast
Snippet: Formerly something of a jewel in the West African crown, this nation has taken huge steps backwards due to recent political driven conflict.

Name: Cook Islands
Snippet: Fifteen islands spread out over an Exclusive Economic Zone of 2,200,000 square kilometres.

Name: Chile
Snippet: A long, thin sliver of land on the western side of the Andes which stands out on any map, this country contains big parts of the Atacama, one of the driest deserts in the world.

Name: Cameroon
Snippet: Sometimes referred to as Africa in Miniature, the terrain includes rain forest, desert plains, mountains and high plateau.

Name: China
Snippet: The world's most populous country and one of the oldest civilizations, with a vast array of cultural and natural treasures among the frenzied development.

Name: Colombia
Snippet: After decades of violence, Colombia is now a much safer destination, offering coffee, jungles, volcanoes and two coastlines with a strong Caribbean feel.

Name: Costa Rica
Snippet: Costa Ricans like to call their country "the Switzerland of Latin America" and indeed it does have mountainous terrain, political neutrality and relative wealth to back up that statement.

Name: Cuba
Snippet: The largest Caribbean island-nation, marked by decades of socialist government.

Name: Cape Verde
Snippet: Tiny Atlantic island group off the coast of Senegal with wonderful beaches.

Name: Cyprus
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Paphos, Limassol and Nicosia.

Name: Czech Republic
Snippet: This country is much more than the home of Kafka fairytale forests and beautiful mountains are a nice addition to the charming cities that survived both wars and communism and the hearty and filling cuisine is just more reason to stay.

Name: Germany
Snippet: Both the most populous and the most economically powerful country in the region, Germany is an incredibly diverse nation that offers everything from skiing in the Alps to sunbathing on the coasts, old towns dating back to the Roman Empire and ultramodern architecture in cities like Frankfurt.

Name: Djibouti
Snippet: Small country across the Gulf of Aden from Yemen and largely Somali in nature.

Name: Denmark
Snippet: The smallest Nordic country features hundreds of islands, rolling farmland, endless beaches and a more continental vibe.

Name: Dominica
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Roseau, Morne Diablotins and Morne Trois Pitons National Park.

Name: Dominican Republic
Snippet: A fast-growing economy with some of the oldest colonial cities in the hemisphere.

Name: Algeria
Snippet: The largest country in Africa.

Name: Ecuador
Snippet: Straddling the Equator, this small country offers incredible diversity across its four regions: the Amazon Rainforest, the Andes, the Pacific Coast and the unique Galapagos Islands.

Name: Estonia
Snippet: The most Nordic of the three Baltic countries, with linguistic connections to Finland, a long coastline, many islands and vast forests.

Name: Egypt
Snippet: Home to some of the world's greatest ancient civilizations, Egypt is famous for its outstanding archaeological sites, among them the pyramids, one of which is the only remaining wonder of the ancient world.

Name: Eritrea
Snippet: This relatively small nation has heavy Arab and Sub-Saharan African influences.

Name: Spain
Snippet: This country is one of Europe's best loved destinations for holidays and living : the culture, nightlife, beaches and history all give human beauty to a country that has so much natural beauty.

Name: Ethiopia
Snippet: Africa's second largest population; one of the world's oldest Christian countries, home to castles, beautiful monasteries, and wonderful food.

Name: Finland
Snippet: A hundred thousand islands and lakes to explore in this bridge to the east.

Name: Fiji
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Matagi Island, Mount Tomanivi and Suva.

Name: Faroe Islands
Snippet: An autonomous territory of Denmark in the Atlantic Ocean with a very distinct culture and sense of national identity.

Name: France
Snippet: France receives more tourists than any other country in the world, and is the largest European Union country by land area.

Name: Gabon
Snippet: Has escaped the strife afflicting other Central African states; rich in oil and mineral reserves and a high biodiversity.

Name: United Kingdom
Snippet: From the rolling hills of England, to the deep valleys of Wales, the beautiful glens of Scotland to the wild coastline of Northern Ireland, the former heart of the world's largest empire remains just as magnificent as it was when it ruled the waves, with unmatched history dating to before the Roman conquest and diverse cities offering a seemingly limitless amount of opportunity.

Name: Grenada
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Grand Etang Lake, Mount Saint Catherine and St. George's.

Name: French Guiana
Snippet: The French part of South America is also part of the European Union and the launchpad of Europe's main spaceport.

Name: Guernsey
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Castle Cornet, Fort Grey and Hauteville House.

Name: Ghana
Snippet: So-called "Africa for Beginners"—West Africa's richest, most-English speaking country, with highly varied landscapes, a few off-the-beaten-path beach getaways, and the solemn, imposing slave castles of the coast west of Accra.

Name: Gibraltar
Snippet: Britain's stronghold on the Spanish coast since before the days of Napoleon.

Name: Greenland
Snippet: A self-governing country that is part of the Kingdom of Denmark, Greenland is a vast island of stark landscapes and midnight sun.

Name: Guinea
Snippet: Some great hill scenery (the Switzerland of Africa), major rainforests and Atlantic beaches, ravaged by decades of political turmoil and lawlessness.

Name: Guadeloupe
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Notre Dame de l'Assomption, FORT Napoleon and Jardin Botanique de Deshaies.

Name: Equatorial Guinea
Snippet: Perhaps one of the continent's most corrupt countries, where massive oil wealth is confiscated by a thuggish government, it is not a terribly safe place to travel, but it has great beaches, laid-back beach bars, and locals speak Spanish.

Name: Greece
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Athens, Thessaloniki and Corfu.

Name: Guatemala
Snippet: One of the centers of Mayan culture and civilization and still blessed with many Mayan sites.

Name: Guam
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Plaza de España, Dulce Nombre de Maria Cathedral Basilica and Fort Santa Agueda.

Name: Guinea-Bissau
Snippet: A former Portuguese colony which has been through lots of struggle since independence and is little visited by travellers.

Name: Guyana
Snippet: The only English-speaking country on mainland South America, featuring highlands, waterfalls and rainforest.

Name: Hong Kong
Snippet: This former British colony markets itself as Asia's World City.

Name: Honduras
Snippet: A long Caribbean coastline graced with beaches and coral reefs, and a mountainous inland home to Mayan ruins and colonial hill towns.

Name: Croatia
Snippet: Croatia has renowned natural beauty, long coastlines, party islands, lots of sun hours and its Venetian history make it one of the Mediterranean's top travel destinations.

Name: Haiti
Snippet: Founded by former slaves who won their freedom and then independence against the might of revolutionary and Napoleonic France.

Name: Hungary
Snippet: A favorite with Easterners during the Cold War, Hungary today is among the often overlooked gems of Central Europe. Don't make that mistake.

Name: Indonesia
Snippet: The world's largest archipelago nation with over 16,000 islands and the largest Muslim-majority country in the world, but also nominally secular and deeply influenced by Hindu and Buddhist culture.

Name: Republic of Ireland
Snippet: Ireland is often called the 'Emerald Isle'. It boasts an expansive and fascinating history, with a landscape that never ceases to astound.

Name: Israel
Snippet: The birthplace of both Judaism and Christianity, with numerous holy sites for Muslims, Druze and Baha'is as well, in addition to places of cultural, historical and prehistoric significance.

Name: Isle of Man
Snippet: A small island between Great Britain and Ireland in the Irish Sea, with its own Celtic language and customs.

Name: India
Snippet: A country of ancient and rich cultural heritage with the Himalayan Mountains in the north, Thar Desert in the west and the Indian Ocean in the south.

Name: Iraq
Snippet: This cradle of civilization is too dangerous for leisure travel, though more intrepid travellers may find Iraqi Kurdistan a congenial place for a visit.

Name: Iran
Snippet: A country full of historic places, a variety of attractions, and ecosystems that range from deserts in the central and southern parts to beautiful humid forests in the north near the Caspian Sea.

Name: Iceland
Snippet: Spectacular scenery of volcanoes, glaciers, geysers, and waterfalls on this North Atlantic island.

Name: Italy
Snippet: The boot-shaped Italian peninsula was the cradle of both the Roman Empire and the Renaissance, and has attracted tourists from afar since before the country was unified in 1870.

Name: Jersey
Snippet: The largest and most developed of the islands, with the most to do.

Name: Jamaica
Snippet: An island of tall mountains, birthplace of reggae and a Commonwealth Realm.

Name: Jordan
Snippet: This country, with its vast deserts, also includes fertile land along the East Bank of the Jordan River and its tributaries, such as the Yarmouk, and contains rich archaeological remains, especially in Jerash and Petra, which is one of the new seven wonders of the world; and the extremely salty Dead Sea.

Name: Japan
Snippet: Isolated until the 19th century, Japan is today the world's third largest economy with both technology and tradition to offer.

Name: Kenya
Snippet: Known for its world-class safaris, beautiful beaches and rich history.

Name: Kyrgyzstan
Snippet: A truly beautiful country high in the mountains, and with the exception of the admittedly fascinating but unsafe Ferghana Valley, Central Asia's easiest and perhaps most pleasant place to visit.

Name: Cambodia
Snippet: Home of the ancient city of Angkor and other remains of the once-powerful Khmer empire, is still recovering from decades of war.

Name: Kiribati
Snippet: The eastern two thirds of this sprawling island nation fall within the scope of Polynesia. Remote and poor, the sun rises first here every day.

Name: Comoros
Snippet: A small island group in the Mozambique Channel and an historic crossroad of cultures.

Name: Saint Kitts and Nevis
Snippet: Known for dinner. Recommended places to visit are Saint Kitts, Basseterre and Nevis.

Name: North Korea
Snippet: The world's most secret society and last remaining outpost of the Cold War.

Name: South Korea
Snippet: A hotspot of innovation and pop culture and in many ways the opposite of its northern neighbor.

Name: Kuwait
Snippet: Probably best known internationally for its brief occupation by Iraq and role in the 1990-1991 Gulf War, Kuwait is an oil-rich emirate that is a destination for laborers and businessmen, generally not for tourists.

Name: Cayman Islands
Snippet: Known for offshore banking, and a great diving destination.

Name: Kazakhstan
Snippet: The world's largest landlocked nation is sparsely populated, dominated by archetypal Central Asian steppe, with deep reserves of fossil fuels, and pockets of beautiful wilderness for outdoors enthusiasts.

Name: Laos
Snippet: The only landlocked country in the region and the most sparsely populated, mainly Buddhist Laos has stunning natural scenery and charming laid-back towns.

Name: Lebanon
Snippet: This small country is diverse in culture, religion, politics and terrain. Beirut in particular has been known for the most part as a very liberal city.

Name: Saint Lucia
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Qualibou, Pitons and Soufriere.

Name: Liechtenstein
Snippet: While you might associate Liechtenstein with shady financial deals and strange politics, this tiny alpine principality by the Rhine is well worth a short stop.

Name: Sri Lanka
Snippet: The pearl of the Orient, has a tropical climate and cultural influences from the rest of South Asia.

Name: Liberia
Snippet: Settled by former African American slaves in the 19th Century, this country has been through murderous conflicts, and it is too dangerous to visit outside Monrovia.

Name: Lesotho
Snippet: The Kingdom in the Sky.

Name: Lithuania
Snippet: An expanding economic market, it has some of the best natural countryside in Europe, mainly hilly, with lowlands in the central region.

Name: Luxembourg
Snippet: This small duchy once laid claims upon the entire Benelux region around 600 years ago.

Name: Latvia
Snippet: A mainly flat, predominately Protestant country, with a lot of Baltic-German and Nordic heritage, lots of woodlands, lakes and rivers.

Name: Libya
Snippet: Large open spaces with more than 90% of the country being desert or semidesert, with some Roman ruins along the coast, but sadly in the middle of a deadly civil war.

Name: Morocco
Snippet: Situated on both the North Atlantic Ocean and Mediterranean Sea.

Name: Monaco
Snippet: A principality on the French riviera, known for Formula One and gambling.

Name: Moldova
Snippet: A pastoral and multi-ethnic country, only considered Balkan due to its cultural ties with Romania.

Name: Montenegro
Snippet: The Bay of Kotor, the Budva Riviera, winter sports and natural scenery, Montenegro is one of the most traveller-friendly countries in the region.

Name: Saint Martin
Snippet: Known for lunch. Recommended places to visit are Mary Star of the Sea Church, Philipsburg and Sandy Ground.

Name: Madagascar
Snippet: Expect the unexpected in the land of the lemurs and the so-called eighth continent.

Name: Marshall Islands
Snippet: A small, isolated atoll nation and home to the former US nuclear test site Bikini Atoll.

Name: Mali
Snippet: A country with a remarkable history and heritage; home to the ancient trade capitals and seats of learning of Djenné and Timbuktu.

Name: Myanmar
Snippet: Ancient country with staggering ethnic diversity, whose history includes both an indigenous empire and being part of the British Empire, now emerging from isolation under a strict military junta and opening up to tourism.

Name: Mongolia
Snippet: A nomadic land of vast spaces and mystic Buddhism.

Name: Macau
Snippet: A former Portuguese colony with liberal gambling laws and beautiful colonial architecture in its UNESCO listed historical city centre.

Name: Northern Mariana Islands
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Saipan, Tinian and Garapan.

Name: Martinique
Snippet: Known for beaches. Recommended places to visit are Co-Cathedral of Our Lady of Assumption, St. Louis Cathedral and Our Lady of the Assumption Church.

Name: Mauritania
Snippet: Interest for the traveller here is primarily centred on the Saharan dune regions.

Name: Montserrat
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Montserrat Volcano Observatory, National Museum of Montserrat and Chances Peak.

Name: Malta
Snippet: A Mediterranean island nation, always at the crossroads of history.

Name: Mauritius
Snippet: An island with a population mainly descended from Indian indentured labourers.

Name: Maldives
Snippet: Home to gorgeous beaches, with a culture influenced by India and the Middle East.

Name: Malawi
Snippet: The warm heart of Africa, around Lake Malawi.

Name: Mexico
Snippet: Mexico is a big tourist attraction for sun-seekers, naturalists, ecotourists and historians; the former flock to Mexico's tropical beaches, while the latter will find everything from Mayan ruins to Spanish colonial history.

Name: Malaysia
Snippet: Multicultural country (including Muslim Malays, mainly Buddhist Chinese, mainly Hindu Indians, and many Orang Asli aboriginal people, especially in Borneo) that ranges from skyscrapers in Kuala Lumpur to jungle-dwelling tribes in Borneo.

Name: Mozambique
Snippet: Relax on the stunningly beautiful beaches and reefs or get into the backcountry and do some exploring.

Name: Namibia
Snippet: Namibia produces some of the world's highest quality diamonds.

Name: New Caledonia
Snippet: Known for dinner. Recommended places to visit are Amédée Lighthouse, Nouméa and Yaté.

Name: Niger
Snippet: Similar to neighbouring Mali and perhaps the most popular Sahelian country with travellers.

Name: Nigeria
Snippet: A vast, dangerous, chaotic, overpopulated, and always fascinating country, with great wealth—little of it shared with its people.

Name: Nicaragua
Snippet: Nicaraguans like to call their country the country of lakes and volcanoes and indeed, those are the two defining geographical features.

Name: Netherlands
Snippet: A flat country that is constantly being changed by the seas.

Name: Norway
Snippet: Famous for deep fjords, steep mountains, countless waterfalls, wooden churches, the Northern Lights and millennial maritime traditions.

Name: Nepal
Snippet: Home to Mount Everest and birthplace of Buddha, popular with adventure tourists, and a place of many rare animals and pure hospitality.

Name: Niue
Snippet: The largest raised coral atoll in the world, halfway between Tonga and the Cook Islands.

Name: New Zealand
Snippet: Although, like most countries, tiny in size compared to Australia, a major destination and widely regarded as one of the most pristine and beautiful countries on earth.

Name: Oman
Snippet: A sultanate that's off the beaten path for most travellers, it is the only country that has a majority of Ibadi Muslims, and it is very rich in beautiful scenery.

Name: Panama
Snippet: The wealthiest country in the region mostly due to the eponymous canal, this country only gained independence in the early 20th century from Colombia.

Name: Peru
Snippet: The historic heartland of the Incas, this country still offers a lot of Inca heritage (Machu Picchu being the most visited site) plus the Nazca lines, made by an earlier culture for a still not entirely clear purpose.

Name: French Polynesia
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Mount Duff, Bora Bora and Manihi.

Name: Papua New Guinea
Snippet: Geographically part of Melanesia, the islands have tropical rainforests, great scenery, and diverse cultures.

Name: Philippines
Snippet: A unique fusion of the Asian traditions of non-confrontation and respect for elders combined with Spanish ideas of machismo, romance and sophistication (plus modern Americanization), the largest Christian nation in the region, and second largest archipelago with 7,641 islands – most with beautiful tropical beaches, warmth and friendly smiles.

Name: Pakistan
Snippet: Rich in culture and history, varying climates and terrains from hot deserts to snowy mountains, and home of 5 of only 14 8,000-metre mountains on earth, but tourism is suffering due to the unpredictable security situation.

Name: Poland
Snippet: This beautiful country has a long and brave history spanning thousands of years.

Name: Puerto Rico
Snippet: A United States territory with bustling nightlife, as well as great inland sceneries.

Name: Portugal
Snippet: This stunning country is bordered by Spain and the picturesque Atlantic Ocean.

Name: Palau
Snippet: A beautiful nation with a lake full of jellyfish, rock islands and an interesting culture.

Name: Paraguay
Snippet: Possibly the least visited country on the continent, in flat Paraguay you can see Jesuit missions, some major rivers and the impressive Itaipú Dam and hear the native Guaraní language.

Name: Qatar
Snippet: This Arabian peninsula is the world's richest country in term of per capita GDP (PPP).

Name: Romania
Snippet: While it's not entirely Balkan (the region of Transylvania lies in Central Europe), Romania offers a wonderful combination of old and new, mixing dance halls with Dracula.

Name: Serbia
Snippet: Historic cities, monasteries, national parks and a good nightlife, Serbia has a lot to offer the traveller.

Name: Russia
Snippet: Northern Asia belongs to Russia.

Name: Rwanda
Snippet: Gorillas in the mist.

Name: Saudi Arabia
Snippet: This oil-rich desert kingdom, subject to some of the harshest interpretations on Islamic Law in the world, is home to the holiest cities for Muslims: Mecca and Medina.

Name: Solomon Islands
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Laulasi Island, Uepi and Santa Cruz Islands.

Name: Seychelles
Snippet: A group of 115 islands northeast of Madagascar and the smallest country in Africa by both area and population.

Name: Sudan
Snippet: One of the largest countries in Africa and home to the world's oldest continuous major civilisations; it has been very prone to conflict.

Name: Sweden
Snippet: The largest Nordic country by area and population is home to endless forests, clear blue lakes and the beautiful archipelagos along its coasts.

Name: Singapore
Snippet: Prosperous, clean and orderly island city-state, with a Chinese majority but with strong Malay and Indian communities, the main business and financial hub of the region.

Name: Slovenia
Snippet: Much more than just another post-Yugoslav state, this small nation has both the Adriatic sea and the Alps, Romance, Slavic and Germanic influences and a well educated population that speaks enough foreign languages to welcome visitors from all around the globe.

Name: Slovakia
Snippet: Often mistaken as simply an appendix of "big brother" Czech Republic, this small ice-hockey crazy nation has made good use of its independence won in 1993 and now offers a unique blend of German, Magyar, Czech and Slovak influences that come together in its capital Bratislava as well as the skiing resorts of Europe's smallest high mountain range, the High Tatra.

Name: Sierra Leone
Snippet: Some of the best beaches anywhere in the world, and huge potential for tourism, but held back by enormous transport infrastructure problems and extreme poverty.

Name: San Marino
Snippet: A microstate claiming to be the world's oldest republic. It has a historic hilltop capital with three old fortresses.

Name: Senegal
Snippet: West Africa's other "visitor-friendly" destination, with tasty food, nice beaches, and French colonial history.

Name: Somalia
Snippet: One of the least visited nations on earth, wrought with political instability, civil war, and rampant kidnapping/abductions.

Name: Suriname
Snippet: This former Dutch colony offers a unique mix of Caribbean, Asian, Dutch and Latin American.

Name: South Sudan
Snippet: The world's newest country, it split off from warring neighbor Sudan in July 2011.

Name: El Salvador
Snippet: The only Central American country without an Atlantic coastline marred by decades of civil war now thankfully in the past.

Name: Syria
Snippet: This historic country was part of the Fertile Crescent in ancient times and shows the imprint of all historical periods since, but is in the throes of a bloody civil war that has not only killed a large number of people and displaced even more, but has also involved wholesale looting and destruction of archaeological relics by the so-called Islamic State organization, one of several fighting in Syria.

Name: Turks and Caicos Islands
Snippet: Fabulous beaches and offshore banking.

Name: Chad
Snippet: Well off-the-beaten-path for all but the hardiest of travellers; very unstable in the north.

Name: Togo
Snippet: A small country that is home to no less than 40 different ethnic groups, and the surreal villages of Tamberma Valley.

Name: Thailand
Snippet: Rich culture and cuisine with frenetic cities, chilled-out beaches, and remains of Buddhist kingdoms, making it a very popular destination with visitors returning time and again.

Name: Tajikistan
Snippet: Central Asia's poorest backwater truly is off the beaten path, but has some incredible landscapes and Persian culture nonetheless.

Name: East Timor
Snippet: One of the world's newest states, a former Portuguese colony on the eastern half of the island of Timor, boasts excellent diving and an unique culture in the region.

Name: Turkmenistan
Snippet: An amalgam of desert moonscapes and arid mountains, dotted with the ruins of great ancient civilizations, and ruled until 2006 by a post-Soviet lunatic cultivating one of the most bizarre cults of personality in history, this is off-the-beaten-path, difficult (courtesy of rotten officialdom), but potentially very rewarding travel.

Name: Tunisia
Snippet: Located in the very centre of Mediterranean Africa.

Name: Tonga
Snippet: The so-called “Friendly islands” and a Kingdom. But traditional and modern cultures are now clashing.

Name: Turkey
Snippet: A very varied country that literally bridges Europe and Asia, it includes the cosmopolitan metropolis of Istanbul, many historical sites, and gorgeous mountains, lakes and coastlines.

Name: Trinidad and Tobago
Snippet: Known for dinner. Recommended places to visit are Port of Spain, Tobago and Chacachacare Lighthouse.

Name: Tuvalu
Snippet: One of the smallest countries in the world in terms of population.

Name: Taiwan
Snippet: The remnants of the Republic of China, and an island of sharp contrasts: lush mountains, skyscrapers, gentle tai-chi and good food.

Name: Tanzania
Snippet: Mt. Kilimanjaro, major game parks and the pre-colonial cities of the Swahili Coast.

Name: Ukraine
Snippet: Known for museums. Recommended places to visit are Swallow's Nest, Marble Cave and Lviv.

Name: Uganda
Snippet: Wildlife abounds and this is the best place for treks into the Congolese jungle to visit the nearly extinct mountain gorillas.

Name: United States
Snippet: One of the largest, most ethnically diverse and multicultural nations on Earth includes some of the world's most famous cities, natural parks of unspeakable beauty, and virtually everything in between.

Name: Uruguay
Snippet: As futbol-crazy as its neighbors of Argentina and Brazil, Uruguay also offers beaches, lovely historic towns, and a laid-back lifestyle.

Name: Uzbekistan
Snippet: With cities such as Samarkand, Bukhara, Khiva, Tashkent, and other old Silk Road citadels, this country has way more than its fair share of culture and history.

Name: Saint Vincent and the Grenadines
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Canouan, Petit Canouan and Tobago Cays.

Name: Venezuela
Snippet: You may think only of oil and socialism, but Venezuela also offers jungles, waterfalls, major cities like Maracaibo and Caracas and Lake Maracaibo, one of the biggest lakes or bays (depending on whom you ask) in the world.

Name: British Virgin Islands
Snippet: Known for diving. Recommended places to visit are Tortola, Queen Elizabeth II Bridge and Virgin Gorda.

Name: Vietnam
Snippet: Firmly marching down the road to capitalism as one of the world's fastest growing economies, Vietnam has a blend of Southeast Asian and Chinese values and culture, and a huge diversity of both natural and cultural attractions.

Name: Vanuatu
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Port-Vila, Malo Island and Aore Island.

Name: Wallis and Futuna
Snippet: Known for natural attractions. Recommended places to visit are Mata Utu, Wallis Island and Futuna Island.

Name: Samoa
Snippet: Two main volcanic islands with luxuriant vegetation, traditional culture and wonderful open-sided houses.

Name: Yemen
Snippet: This beautiful country, famous for its traditional adobe highrises, fertile highlands and delicious food, is in the throes of a brutal civil war and a very destructive international bombing campaign.

Name: South Africa
Snippet: One of the richest countries in Africa has its share of wildlife and tourist-friendly sites.

Name: Zambia
Snippet: A landlocked country in the north of Southern Africa.

Name: Zimbabwe
Snippet: Once known as the breadbasket of Africa, widely known for its famous landmarks, tourist attractions and varied scenery.
